"Galford G.L., Melillo J.M., Kicklighter D.W., Mustard J.F., Cronin T.W., Cerri C.E.P., Cerri C.C.","Historical carbon emissions and uptake from the agricultural frontier of the Brazilian Amazon",2011,"Ecological Applications","21","3",,"750","763",,,10.1890/09-1957.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955516574&partnerID=40&md5=9b6e8bb0eb6ad4a88856be6eecd95d90","Ecosystems Center, Marine Biological Laboratory, Woods Hole, MA 02543, United States; Geological Sciences, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912, United States; Centro de Escola Superior de Agricultura Luiz de Queiroz, Universidade de São Paulo, Piracicaba, Brazil; Energia Nuclear Na Agricultura, Universidade de São Paulo, Piracicaba, Brazil; Earth Institute at Columbia University, Geosciences 102A, Palisades, NY 10964, United States; Earth, Atmospheric, and Planetary Sciences, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge, MA 02139, United States","Galford, G.L., Ecosystems Center, Marine Biological Laboratory, Woods Hole, MA 02543, United States, Geological Sciences, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912, United States, Earth Institute at Columbia University, Geosciences 102A, Palisades, NY 10964, United States; Melillo, J.M., Ecosystems Center, Marine Biological Laboratory, Woods Hole, MA 02543, United States; Kicklighter, D.W., Ecosystems Center, Marine Biological Laboratory, Woods Hole, MA 02543, United States; Mustard, J.F., Geological Sciences, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912, United States; Cronin, T.W., Ecosystems Center, Marine Biological Laboratory, Woods Hole, MA 02543, United States, Earth, Atmospheric, and Planetary Sciences, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Cambridge, MA 02139, United States; Cerri, C.E.P., Centro de Escola Superior de Agricultura Luiz de Queiroz, Universidade de São Paulo, Piracicaba, Brazil; Cerri, C.C., Energia Nuclear Na Agricultura, Universidade de São Paulo, Piracicaba, Brazil","Tropical ecosystems play a large and complex role in the global carbon cycle. Clearing of natural ecosystems for agriculture leads to large pulses of CO 2 to the atmosphere from terrestrial biomass. Concurrently, the remaining intact ecosystems, especially tropical forests, may be sequestering a large amount of carbon from the atmosphere in response to global environmental changes including climate changes and an increase in atmospheric CO 2 Here we use an approach that integrates census-based historical land use reconstructions, remote-sensing-based contemporary land use change analyses, and simulation modeling of terrestrial biogeochemistry to estimate the net carbon balance over the period 1901-2006 for the state of Mato Grosso, Brazil, which is one of the most rapidly changing agricultural frontiers in the world. By the end of this period, we estimate that of the state's 925 225 km2, 221 092 km 2 have been converted to pastures and 89 533 km 2 have been converted to croplands, with forest-to-pasture conversions being the dominant land use trajectory but with recent transitions to croplands increasing rapidly in the last decade. These conversions have led to a cumulative release of 4.8 Pg C to the atmosphere, with ∼80% from forest clearing and 20% from the clearing of cerrado. Over the same period, we estimate that the residual undisturbed ecosystems accumulated 0.3 Pg C in response to CO 2 fertilization. Therefore, the net emissions of carbon from Mato Grosso over this period were 4.5 Pg C. Net carbon emissions from Mato Grosso since 2000 averaged 146 Tg C/yr, on the order of Brazil's fossil fuel emissions during this period. These emissions were ssociated with the expansion of croplands to grow soybeans. While alternative management regimes in croplands, including tillage, fertilization, and cropping patterns promote carbon storage in ecosystems, they remain a small portion of the net carbon balance for the region. This detailed accounting of a region's carbon balance is the type of foundation analysis needed by the new United Nations Collaborative Programmme for Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and Forest Degradation (REDD). © 2011 by the Ecological Society of America.","Amazon; Carbon emissions; Cerrado; CO 2fertilization; Crops; Global warming; Land cover and land use change; Mato Grosso Brazil; Pasture; Soils; Terrestrial ecosystems model; United Nations Collaborative Programmme for Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and Forest Degradation (REDD)","carbon; agricultural land; agricultural practice; alternative agriculture; biogeochemistry; biological uptake; biomass; carbon cycle; carbon emission; deforestation; environmental degradation; fossil fuel; global warming; land use change; numerical model; pasture; remote sensing; soybean; terrestrial environment; agriculture; air pollutant; article; biological model; Brazil; chemistry; computer simulation; ecosystem; environmental monitoring; history; metabolism; plant; soil; time; tropic climate; Agriculture; Air Pollutants; Brazil; Carbon; Computer Simulation; Ecosystem; Environmental Monitoring; History, 20th Century; History, 21st Century; Models, Biological; Plants; Soil; Time Factors; Tropical Climate; Amazonas [Brazil]; Brazil; Glycine max",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; Air Pollutants; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Soil",,,,"Asner, G.P., Broadbent, E.N., Oliveira, P.J.C., Keller, M., Knapp, D.E., Silva, J.M.M., Condition and fate of logged forests in the Brazilian Amazon (2006) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 103 (34), pp. 12947-12950. , DOI 10.1073/pnas.0604093103; Asner, G.P., Knapp, D.E., Broadbent, E.N., Oliveira, P.J.C., Keller, M., Silva, J.N., Selective logging in the Brazilian Amazon (2005) Science, 310, pp. 480-482; Balesdent, J., Chenu, C., Balabane, M., Relationship of soil organic matter dynamics to physical protection and tillage (2000) Soil and Tillage Research, 53 (3-4), pp. 215-230. , DOI 10.1016/S0167-1987(99)00107-5, PII S0167198799001075; Batjes, N., Bernoux, M., Ce